{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20180911154248|859079849","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Ralph_Abraham_(politician)","to":"Ralph Abraham (politician)"}],"pages":{"44279997":{"pageid":44279997,"ns":0,"title":"Ralph Abraham (politician)","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-10-12T18:35:55Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{for|the mathematician|Ralph Abraham (mathematician)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Ralph Abraham\n|image       = Ralph Abraham official congressional photo.jpg\n|state       = [[Louisiana]]\n|district    = {{ushr|LA|5|5th}}\n|term_start  = January 3, 2015\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = [[Vance McAllister]]\n|successor   = \n|birth_name  = Ralph Lee Abraham Jr.\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1954|9|16}}\n|birth_place = [[Monroe, Louisiana]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse      = Dianne Abraham\n|children    = 3\n|education   = [[Louisiana State University]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]], [[Doctor of Veterinary Medicine|DVM]])<br>[[LSU Health Sciences Center New Orleans|Louisiana State University, New Orleans]] ([[Doctor of Medicine|MD]])\n|allegiance  = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch      = [[Mississippi National Guard]], [[United States Coast Guard Auxiliary]]\n}}\n'''Ralph Lee Abraham Jr.''' (born September 16, 1954),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://info.cqrollcall.com/rs/cqrc/images/CQNews_NewMemberGuide2014.pdf |title=Guide to the New Congress |publisher=[[Roll Call]] |accessdate=December 6, 2014}}</ref> is an American physician and former veterinarian from [[Alto, Louisiana]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Broach |first1=Drew |title=Just where does Louisiana Congressman Ralph Abraham actually live? |url=https://www.nola.com/politics/index.ssf/2017/10/where_does_ralph_abraham_live.html |accessdate=21 July 2018 |publisher=NOLA.com - The Times-Picayune |date=25 Oct 2017}}</ref> who won election on [[United States House of Representatives elections in Louisiana, 2014#District 5|December 6, 2014]], as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] to represent {{ushr|LA|5}} in the [[United States House of Representatives]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.myarklamiss.com/story/d/story/nela-doctor-running-for-congress/91351/n2Wcnu8DrkG-bKuzagMnNg |title=NELA Doctor Running for Congress |date=May 30, 2014 |accessdate=June 2, 2014 |work=myarklamiss.com}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nAbraham is the son of the former Marlene Posey (1932\u20132015), a retired [[educator]], and Ralph Abraham, Sr. (1933\u20131980).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thenewsstar.com/story/news/local/2015/07/29/congressman-abrahams-mother-dies/30830519/ |title=Congressman Abraham's mother, 83, dies |author=Greg Hilburn |work=The Monroe News-Star |date=July 29, 2015 |accessdate=July 30, 2015}}</ref> His paternal grandparents were emigrants from [[Lebanon]].<ref name=\"Viebeck\">{{cite web|last1=Viebeck|first1=Elise|title=Arab-American Republican lawmakers divided on Trump's travel ban|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/arab-american-republican-lawmakers-divided-on-trumps-travel-ban/2017/02/01/d75e7d10-e8cf-11e6-80c2-30e57e57e05d_story.html|website=Washington Post|date=February 1, 2017 |accessdate=28 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe graduated from [[Louisiana State University]] School of Veterinary Medicine, in [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana|Baton Rouge]] in 1980, and was a practicing veterinarian for 10 years.<ref name=avma>{{cite news|last1=Goddard|first1=Valerie|title=Is there a job Ralph Abraham can't do?|url=https://www.avma.org/News/JAVMANews/Pages/150801j.aspx|accessdate=October 29, 2016|agency=American Veterinary Medical Association|publisher=JAVMAnews|date=July 15, 2015}}</ref> He returned to [[Louisiana State University School of Medicine]] for a medical degree in 1994, and practiced family medicine.<ref name=avma/>\n\nAbraham has served in the [[United States Coast Guard Auxiliary]] and the [[Mississippi National Guard]].<ref name=newsstar>{{cite web |url=http://www.thenewsstar.com/story/news/local/2014/11/22/abraham-remained-consistent-ersistent/19430723/ |title=Abraham: 'We remained consistent and persistent' |author=Greg Hilburn |date=November 22, 2014 |work= [[The News-Star|The Monroe News-Star]] |accessdate=December 7, 2014}}</ref> He and his wife, Dianne, have three children.<ref name=newsstar/>  He has been an aviation medical examiner.<ref name=\"Medical Examiner Citation\">{{cite web |last1=Abraham |first1=Ralph |title=Medical Examiner |url=https://www.ralphabraham.com/about/ |website=www.RalphAbraham.com |publisher=Abraham for Congress Campaign |accessdate=20 Jul 2018}}</ref>\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Tenure===\nAbraham defeated his [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] opponent, [[Mayor]] [[Jamie Mayo]] of [[Monroe, Louisiana|Monroe]], by a margin of 134,612 votes (64.2 percent) to 75,004 (35.8 percent).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://staticresults.sos.la.gov/12062014/12062014_23.html |title=Runoff election returns, December 6, 2014 |publisher=[[Louisiana Secretary of State]] |accessdate=December 6, 2014}}</ref> He was sworn into office in the [[114th United States Congress]] on January 3, 2015.\n\nAfter his election, Abraham chose Luke J. Letlow, his campaign manager, as chief of staff.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thenewsstar.com/story/news/local/2014/12/10/letlow-named-abrahams-chief-staff/20201499/ |title=Letlow named Abraham's chief of staff |author=Greg Hilburn |date=December 10, 2014 |work=The Monroe News-Star |accessdate=December 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn June, 2017, Abraham co-sponsored the [[Civil Rights Uniformity Act of 2017]].<ref name=\"Gamard8917\">{{cite web|last1=Gamard|first1=Sarah|title=Louisiana congressman part of effort to end 'gender' debate|url=https://www.salon.com/2017/08/09/louisiana-congressman-part-of-effort-to-end-gender-debate/|website=Salon|accessdate=31 December 2017|date=9 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, Abraham endorsed the nomination by [[U.S. President]] [[Donald Trump]] of [[Terry Doughty]], also of Richland Parish, for a seat on the [[United States District Court for the Western District of Louisiana]], based in Monroe. The selection also carries the backing of [[United States Senate|U.S. Senators]] [[Bill Cassidy]] and [[John Neely Kennedy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenewsstar.com/story/news/2017/08/03/rayville-judge-nominated-federal-judgeship/539102001/|title=Trump taps Rayville judge for federal bench|publisher=''[[The News-Star|The Monroe News-Star]]''|author=Barbara Leader and Greg Hilburn|date=August 4, 2017|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, Abraham voted in favor of the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017|Tax Cuts and Jobs Act]].<ref name=\"Almukhtar\">{{cite web|last1=Almukhtar|first1=Sarah|title=How Each House Member Voted on the Tax Bill|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/12/19/us/politics/tax-bill-house-live-vote.html?_r=1|website=The New York Times|accessdate=31 December 2017|date=19 December 2017}}</ref> After voting, Abraham stated that \"This is going to be a great tax bill, and great tax reform not only for Louisiana but for the United States.\" He says that businesses will benefit greatly and be able to \"reinvest in their infrastructure, reinvest in their employees.\" He says that wages will increase and job opportunities will grow.<ref name=\"WWL122017\">{{cite web|title=Louisiana's Republican delegation supports tax reform bill|url=http://www.wwl.com/articles/louisianas-republican-delegation-supports-tax-reform-bill|website=WWL|accessdate=31 December 2017|date=20 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Agriculture|Committee on Agriculture]]'''\n** [[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on Conservation and Forestry|Subcommittee on Conservation and Forestry]]\n** [[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management|Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Science, Space and Technology|Committee on Science, Space and Technology]]'''\n** [[United States House Science Subcommittee on Space|Subcommittee on Space]] (Vice-Chair)\n** [[United States House Science Subcommittee on Research and Technology|Subcommittee on Research and Technology]]\n** [[United States House Science Subcommittee on Oversight|Subcommittee on Oversight]] (Chair)\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Armed Services]]'''<ref>{{cite web |title=Abraham assignment gives cover for Barksdale, Fort Polk |url=https://www.thenewsstar.com/story/news/2017/01/10/abraham-assignment-gives-cover-barksdale-fort-polk/96387816/ |website=TheNewsStar.com |publisher=The Monroe News-Star |author=Greg Hilburn and Deborah Barfield Berry |accessdate=21 July 2018}}</ref>\n** [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Emerging Threats and Capabilities|Subcommittee on Emerging Threats and Capabilities]]\n** [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Seapower and Projection Forces|Subcommittee on Seapower and Projection Forces]]\n** [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Military Personnel|Subcommittee on Military Personnel]]\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* [[Congressional Western Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://westerncaucus.house.gov/about/membership.htm|publisher=Congressional Western Caucus|date=|accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n* [http://www.ciclt.net/sn/pol/poc_detail.aspx?P_ID=&ClientCode=masc&LegComID=20963 Coast Guard Caucus]\n* [https://preservationaction.org/caucus/ Historic Preservation Caucus]\n* [https://roe.house.gov/roedoctorscaucus/ GOP Doctor's Caucus]\n* [https://abraham.house.gov/about/committees-and-caucuses Mississippi River Caucus]<ref>{{cite web |title=Ralph Abraham, Bio and Caucus List |url=http://caucus.militarytimes.com/speaker/ralph-abraham/#.W3J5ENhKgWp |website=MilitaryTimes.com |publisher=Military Times |accessdate=14 August 2018}}</ref>\n* [https://palazzo.house.gov/ngrcc/membership.htm Congressional National Guard and Reserve Components Caucus]\n* [http://caucus.militarytimes.com/speaker/ralph-abraham/#.W3J3A9hKgWo National Guard Youth Challenge Caucus]\n* [http://congressionalsportsmen.org/uploads/home/115th_CSC_Roster.pdf Congressional Sportsmen's Caucus]\n* [http://caucus.militarytimes.com/speaker/ralph-abraham/#.W3J3A9hKgWo Veteran's Caucus]\n* [[Veterinary Medicine Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members of the Veterinary Medicine Caucus|author=|url=https://schrader.house.gov/committees/veterinary-medicine-caucus.htm|format=| publisher=Veterinary Medicine Caucus |date=|accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\n\n===Domestic issues ===\n\n==== Agriculture ====\n\nIn March 2017, Representative Abraham visited with about seventy farmers from the agricultural [[Lobbying|lobby]], the [[Louisiana Farm Bureau Federation]]. He told the farmers, \"Food security is national security. Agriculture is at the forefront of the fight because any interruption in the food supply or a compromise in its safety goes right to the heart of the nation.\"<ref name=lfbf>{{cite web|url=\nhttp://www.thenewsstar.com/story/news/2017/03/17/congressman-abraham-ag-americas-thin-green-line/99264888/|title=Rep. Abraham: Ag is America's 'thin green line'|publisher=''[[The News-Star|The Monroe News-Star]]''|author=Greg Hilburn|date=March 17, 2017|accessdate=March 18, 2017}}</ref> Marty Wooldridge, a cattleman from [[Caddo Parish, Louisiana|Caddo Parish]] said that Abraham's slogan \"Food security is national security\" should be incorporated into the slogan of the Farm Bureau. Abraham, Louisiana's only member on the House Agriculture Committee, defined his job in part to \"educating members whose districts might be deeply metropolitan and who have no perspective on the importance of agriculture.\"<ref name=lfbf/> In 2018, Abraham was named to the conference committee for the 2018 Farm Bill. The conference committee will resolve differences in the House and the Senate version of the Farm Bill.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenewsstar.com/story/news/2018/07/18/abraham-craft-final-farm-bill-language/797847002/|title=Abraham to craft final Farm Bill language|last=Hilburn|first=Greg|date=July 18, 2018|work=The Monroe News-Star|access-date=July 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Gun law====\n\nIn the wake of the [[2016 Orlando nightclub shooting]], Abraham offered thoughts and prayers. He stressed that the shooter had pledged allegiance to [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIS]] and asked for the public to prayer for law enforcement and service members who fight terrorism.<ref name=\"Berkowitz61616\">{{cite web|last1=Berkowitz|first1=Bonnie|last2=Cai|first2=Weiyi|last3=Lu|first3=Denise|last4=Gamio|first4=Lazaro|title=Everything lawmakers said (and didn't say) after the Orlando mass shooting|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/national/how-lawmakers-responded-to-the-orlando-mass-shooting/|website=Washington Post|accessdate=31 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==== Health care ====\n\nAbraham believes the [[Affordable Care Act]] should be repealed. He opposes the expansion of [[Medicaid]].<ref name=debate>{{cite web |url=http://www.thenewsstar.com/story/news/politics/2014/11/20/mayo-abraham-face-th-district-debate/70035864/ |title=Mayo, Abraham face off in 5th District debate |author=Kaleb Causey |date=November 20, 2014 |work=The Monroe News-Star |accessdate=December 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Economic issues ===\n\n==== Tax reform ====\n\nHe supports simplifying the tax code.<ref name=debate/>\n\n==== Jobs ====\n\nAbraham supports [[equal pay for women]].<ref name=debate/>\n\n=== International issues ===\n\n==== Gas &  oil ====\n\nAbraham was in favor of the [[Keystone Pipeline]].<ref name=debate/>\n\n==== Immigration ====\n\nRegarding [[illegal immigration]], Abraham opposes [[amnesty]] and supports strengthening border security.<ref name=debate/>  Abraham supported President [[Donald Trump]]'s 2017 [[Executive Order 13769|executive order]] to temporarily halt [[immigration]] from the seven specified nations until the development of more enhanced screening methods. His spokesman said \"Dr. Abraham generally supports President Trump's temporary suspension of the refugee and immigration admittance program. Dr. Abraham agrees with President Trump that we must take all necessary steps to protect American citizens from potential terrorism threats, and this temporary measure from the President will allow for a thorough review of our policies and procedures for vetting applicants from war-torn areas.\"<ref name=\"Blake1\">{{cite web|last1=Blake|first1=Aaron|title=Coffman, Gardner join Republicans against President Trump's travel ban; here's where the rest stand|url=http://www.denverpost.com/2017/01/29/republicans-on-trump-travel-ban/|website=Denver Post|accessdate=30 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Social issues ===\n\n==== Abortion ====\n\nAbraham opposes [[late term abortion]]s. In May 2005, he stated \"As a doctor, I know and I can attest that this bill is backed by scientific research showing that babies can indeed feel pain at 20 weeks, if not before\" .<ref name=\"Morris10417\">{{cite web|last1=Morris|first1=Meagan|title=Passed abortion ban cited 'fetal pain,' but what does science say about it?|url=https://www.metro.us/news/the-big-stories/abortion-ban-can-fetuses-feel-pain|website=Metro US|accessdate=31 December 2017|language=en|date=4 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==== Cannabis ====\n\nAbraham has a \"D\" rating from [[NORML]] for his voting history regarding [[cannabis]]-related causes. Abraham opposes veterans having access to medical marijuana if recommended by their [[Veterans Health Administration]] doctor and if it is legal for medicinal purposes in their state of residence.<ref name=\"NORML\">{{cite web|title=Louisiana Scorecard|url=http://norml.org/congressional-scorecard/louisiana|website=NORML|accessdate=31 December 2017|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n==== LGBT ====\n\nAbraham supports efforts to ban [[transgender]] people from serving in the  military \"100 percent.\"<ref name=\"Gamard8917\" />\n\n==Election of 2016==\nIn his bid for reelection in 2016, Abraham defeated one challenger, fellow Republican Billy Burkette<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thenewsstar.com/story/news/local/2016/11/08/abraham-reelected-5th-district-seat/93447078/|title=Abraham reelected in 5th district seat|last=Mott|first=Ashley|date=November 9, 2016|website=Monroe News Star|publisher=|access-date=November 13, 2016}}</ref> of [[Baton Rouge]], a former [[constable]] in [[East Feliciana Parish]] and a former chairman of the Louisiana Band of [[Choctaw]] Indians. Burkette claimed in his campaign that the [[Environmental Protection Agency]] has issued overly strict regulations that hamper [[farming]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenewsstar.com/story/news/local/2016/11/05/incumbent-abraham-faces-burkette-5th-district-race/93288812/|title=Incumbent Abraham faces Burkette in 5th district race|author=Ashley Mott|date=November 5, 2016|publisher=''Monroe News-Star''|accessdate=November 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Election of 2018==\nAbraham faces three challengers in the 2018 primary election. Billy Burkette, an Independent from Pride, La; Jessee Carlton Fleenor, a Democrat from Loranger, La; and Kyle Randol, a Libertarian from Monroe, La.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ralph Abraham has three challengers for congressional seat |url=http://www.knoe.com/content/news/Ralph-Abraham-has-three-challengers-for-congressional-seat-488762631.html |accessdate=21 July 2018 |publisher=KNOE.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Portalbar|Biography|Louisiana|Politics|Medicine|Baptist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://abraham.house.gov/ Congressman Ralph Abraham] official U.S. House website\n* [https://www.ralphabraham.com/ Campaign website]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Louisiana/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Ralph_Abraham_%5BR-5%5D|Ralph Abraham}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=A000374 | votesmart=155414 | fec=H4LA05221 | congress=ralph-abraham/A000374}}\n* {{C-SPAN|ralphabraham}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox\n| state = Louisiana\n| district = 5\n| before = [[Vance McAllister]]\n| start = January 3, 2015\n}}\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Donald Norcross]]<br /><small>D-[[New Jersey]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=''[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]''|years=312th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Pete Aguilar]]<br /><small>D-[[California]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{LA-FedRep}}\n{{LARepresentatives}}\n{{USCongRep-start|congresses= 114th\u2013115th [[United States Congress]]es |state=[[Louisiana]]}}\n{{USCongRep/LA/114}}\n{{USCongRep/LA/115}}\n{{USCongRep-end}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Abraham, Ralph}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Louisiana Republicans]]\n[[Category:People from Mangham, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Monroe, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:American politicians of Lebanese descent]]\n[[Category:American veterinarians]]\n[[Category:Physicians from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Louisiana State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Baptists from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:United States Coast Guard personnel]]\n